    {
        "content": "<p>I am a beginner in the subject . So I am seeking prior apology if  I sound stupid. <br>\nLet <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> be the category of Sets . A Grothendieck Topos  is a Category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span>-valued Sheaves over a site internal to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span>. According to <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Grothendieck+topos#Giraud\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Grothendieck+topos#Giraud</a> a Grothendieck Topos can also be defined as a locally small category satisfying some properties  called <em>Giraud's Axioms</em>. I do not know the Proof of the Giraud's theorem yet which characterises Grothendieck Topos in an Axiomatic way. Hopefully I will learn it soon in near future. But first I want to understand the statement that is  \"<em>what Giraud's Axiom actually tells us</em>\". <br>\nIn particular according to <em>Wiki article</em>  <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topos#Grothendieck_topoi_(topoi_in_geometry)\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topos#Grothendieck_topoi_(topoi_in_geometry)</a> it is mentioned \" <em>The main utility of this notion of Topos is in the abundance of situations in mathematics where topological heuristics are very effective, but an honest topological space is lacking; it is sometimes possible to find a topos formalizing the heuristic</em>\". I can   understand or technically feel that the notion of Topos expressed as <em>Category of sheaves over a site</em> expresses this fact . (In fact in the paper <em>Convenient Categories of Smooth Spaces  by Baez and Hoffnung</em> <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/0807.1704.pdf\">https://arxiv.org/pdf/0807.1704.pdf</a>  the category of generalized smooth spaces are described as the category of concrete sheaves on a concrete site). <br>\n<strong>My question is the following:</strong><br>\n<em>How a Grothendieck Topos defined using <em>Giraud's Axioms</em> can be seen in a geometric way(The statement of Wikipedia I mentioned previously)?</em><br>\n<strong>Thank You</strong></p>",
        "id": 203287817,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1594224748
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can see a Grothendieck topos as a the category of sets parametrized over some \"generalized space\". For example, sheaves over a topological space are, informally, sets parametrized over this topological space. <br>\nIf you want to make this precise, then you need to replace \"sets parametrized over a space\" by the notion of local homeomorphism.</p>\n<p>Giraud's axioms hold in the category of sets, and then the idea is that they also hold for \"sets parametrized over some generalized space\".<br>\nThey are concerned with the more \"geometrical\" features of working with sets. For example, the axiom about equivalence relations explains very accurately how the \"gluing\" of sets works.</p>",
        "id": 203315168,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1594238403
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"282722\">@Jens Hemelaer</span> Thank you very much! Just to make sure.. By  <em>\"If you want to make <strong>this</strong> precise, then you need to replace \"sets parametrized over a space\" by the notion of local homeomorphism.\"</em> do you mean Etale spaces over the space?<br>\nAlso what is meant by <strong>this</strong> here?<br>\nSo as you suggested if we identify Set valued Sheaves on a space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> with Etale spaces over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> then can you please explain in little details how will it be <strong>convenient</strong> to see  the geometric interpretation of <em>Giraud's Axioms</em>?</p>",
        "id": 203324922,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1594243208
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The advantage is that one can treat the objects of Grothendieck toposes as if they are spaces over some base and perform \"geometric\" operations on these spaces, and the resulting constructions will behave (from a categorical perspective) like they do over topological spaces.</p>",
        "id": 203326873,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1594244200
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Even when this is not true in a precise sense, the structural similarity typically allows geometric intuition to be extended to a form that makes sense in any (Grothendieck) topos</p>",
        "id": 203326968,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1594244256
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277473\">@[Mod] Morgan Rogers</span>  Thanks! I got your point. But do identifying sheaves over a space as Etale spaces over the space will also help in understanding the Geometric Interpretation of Giraud's Axioms? (<strong>Note</strong>: <em>I did not read the proof of Giraud's Theorem yet.. So I may sound very stupid</em>)</p>",
        "id": 203330002,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1594246199
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"318500\">ADITTYA CHAUDHURI</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos.20theory/topic/Grothendieck.20Topos.20and.20Giraud's.20Axioms/near/203324922\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"282722\">Jens Hemelaer</span> Thank you very much! Just to make sure.. By  <em>\"If you want to make <strong>this</strong> precise, then you need to replace \"sets parametrized over a space\" by the notion of local homeomorphism.\"</em> do you mean Etale spaces over the space?<br>\nAlso what is meant by <strong>this</strong> here?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, I use local homeomorphism as a synonym for étale space here. And by 'this' I meant the concept of seeing objects of the topos as \"sets parametrized over a space\".</p>",
        "id": 203360968,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1594282861
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For me, one direction of Giraud's theorem is easier than the other one. The easier part is proving that the category of sheaves on a Grothendieck site satisfies Giraud's axioms (first prove it for categories of presheaves, then use that the sheafification functor has very good properties).</p>\n<p>Regarding the geometric interpretation of the axioms:<br>\nColimits are very geometrical, because they are about gluing things. Now take for example the third axiom <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Grothendieck+topos#Giraud\">here</a>: a Grothendieck topos has finite coproducts that are disjoint and pullback-stable.<br>\nThis means that you can visualize a coproduct of two objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> as \"just putting <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> together\".<br>\nIf you look at the copy of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span></span></span></span> and the copy of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> inside <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>⊔</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\sqcup B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊔</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>, then their intersection is empty.<br>\nPullback-stability says for example that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>⊔</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>×</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>≃</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>I</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>⊔</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>I</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(A \\sqcup B) \\times I \\simeq (A \\times I) \\sqcup (B \\times I)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊔</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≃</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊔</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, so if you visualize <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> as a line or interval, then this is the behaviour that you would expect, geometrically.</p>\n<p>When visualizing things, it helps to see how things work at the level of points (although not all Grothendieck toposes have enough points).<br>\nBy definition, taking the \"fiber\" above a point in a topos preserves colimits and finite limits. So a colimit or a finite limit of étale spaces will still be a colimit or finite limit if you zoom in to the fiber above one point.</p>",
        "id": 203363067,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1594284651
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A fun consequence of pullback-stability of coproducts:<br>\nTake the initial object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>, this is the empty coproduct. Pullback-stability says that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>×</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>≃</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0 \\times I \\simeq 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≃</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> for all objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span>. This expresses that the initial object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> is \"really empty\".</p>\n<p>A counter-example where this pullback-stability of coproducts does not hold, is the category of pointed sets. The initial object is the set with one element. However, if you take the product of this initial object with some pointed set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\">≠</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I \\neq 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.69444em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"rlap\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"inner\"><span class=\"mrel\"></span></span><span class=\"fix\"></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.19444em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>, <br>\nyou get <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>×</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\">≠</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0 \\times I = I \\neq 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.69444em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"rlap\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"inner\"><span class=\"mrel\"></span></span><span class=\"fix\"></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.19444em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>. So the initial object was not \"really empty\", and as a result the category of pointed sets is not a Grothendieck topos.</p>",
        "id": 203363616,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1594285055
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"282722\">@Jens Hemelaer</span> Thanks a lot for the explanation. I got the geometric motivation.</p>\n<p>Can you please explain in little detail what did you mean by \"<em>By definition, taking the \"fiber\" above a point in a topos preserves colimits and finite limits. So a colimit or a finite limit of étale spaces will still be a colimit or finite limit if you zoom in to the fiber above one point.</em>\"<br>\n For me fiber over point <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span></span></span></span> is something like this<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/CSpwNgFlQxJj0x17Qpu_okxB/taaaa.png\">taaaa.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/CSpwNgFlQxJj0x17Qpu_okxB/taaaa.png\" title=\"taaaa.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/CSpwNgFlQxJj0x17Qpu_okxB/taaaa.png\"></a></div><p>where \"1\" is a terminal object in the category. I did not get the line  <strong>taking \"fibre\"   above a point in a topos preserves colimits and finite limits</strong> .</p>\n<p><em>I observed another geometric interpretation</em> in the the <strong>2nd Axiom</strong> <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Grothendieck+topos#Giraud\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Grothendieck+topos#Giraud</a> that is the existence of finite limits and hence existence of terminal object which is ensuring that we can talk about  <em>fibre over a point</em>  where  by a <em>point</em> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span></span></span></span> in an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> of the topos I actually mean a morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>→</mo><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x:1 \\rightarrow M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> .  So I feel literally they behave like points!</p>",
        "id": 203381140,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1594299122
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There are two different meanings of \"point\" here which arise from the blurred distinction between topos-as-category and topos-as-space. If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is an object of a topos, then a \"point of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>\" is a map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>:</mo><mo>∗</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x : * \\to X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.46528em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> like you write above. On the other hand, a \"point of the topos\" itself is a point of the imaginary space on which the topos is the category of sheaves. On the category level, it corresponds to <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/point+of+a+topos\">a certain kind of functor</a>.</p>",
        "id": 203382835,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1594300076
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276480\">@Reid Barton</span> Thanks a lot for the clarification. Did you mean that  since the category  <strong>Sets</strong> is a terminal object  in the 2-category of Grothendieck Topos so a geometric morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>s</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x: Sets \\rightarrow E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">s</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span></span></span></span> can be thought as a point in the Topos <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span></span></span></span>?(Precisely due to the same reason I explained previously)</p>",
        "id": 203385553,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1594301711
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By a point, I meant a point of the topos <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span></span> in the sense of a geometric morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x: \\mathbf{Sets} \\to \\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68611em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">s</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span></span>. Taking the fiber is then applying <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x^*</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.688696em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.688696em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, the left adjoint part of the geometric morphism. In order for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span></span></span></span> to qualify as a geometric morphism, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x^*</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.688696em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.688696em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> should preserve colimits and finite limits.</p>\n<p>The diagram that you posted is good intuition. In fact, for each geometric morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span></span>, there is an associated topos <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}/X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/over-topos\">slice topos</a> over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>. If you think of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span></span> as a generalized space, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}/X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is the étale space over it, corresponding to the object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>Now, if you have a geometric morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x : \\mathbf{Sets} \\to \\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68611em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">s</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span></span>, then there is the following pullback diagram in the 2-category of Grothendieck toposes:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/eZG-kacpmPudquwvgKBAlAWS/Screenshot-2020-07-09-at-16.08.58.png\">Screenshot-2020-07-09-at-16.08.58.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/eZG-kacpmPudquwvgKBAlAWS/Screenshot-2020-07-09-at-16.08.58.png\" title=\"Screenshot-2020-07-09-at-16.08.58.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/eZG-kacpmPudquwvgKBAlAWS/Screenshot-2020-07-09-at-16.08.58.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 203390023,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1594303862
